text: And for all the shit talking about a young girl, heres her info so shut the fuck up. Shes more talented than you could ever be......  Milly was born in Tampa, Florida to business owners Michelle and Eric Shapiro. She was educated at the Community Montessori School from 18 mos. until 10 years old, when she moved to New York to pursue her career as an actress-singer. Inspired by her sister, Abigail, she began vocal training at the age of 3 and acting at 5 when she began performing. She was discovered at the age of 10 and began training as a professional actress-singer, when she moved to New York to accept the role of Matilda in Matilda the Musical on Broadway.  Since then, she and her sister created a series of concerts and cabarets at 54 Below to support the Anti-Bullying Movement. She was then cast as Sally Brown in the first off-Broadway all-youth production of You're A Good Man Charlie Brown. Charlie in Hereditary was her first film role and she is equally passionate about both mediums. She continues working on her craft and feels that there will always be something to learn. Milly is known for her unique spirit and passionate approach to all she experiences. In her free time, she enjoys reading, watching Anime and loves playing with her two dogs. She hopes her future roles continue to challenge her imagination and are fun to play.
author: Mary Cee

author: Haley Schwarz

text: I watched it yesterday and let me just say that I like all horror movies.. campy, gory, jump scares, etc.. I just know what I'm watching and go into it with the right mindset.. however I believe that this movie is imo a true horror film to the core.. I mean the family tragedy that takes place in the film drowns you in dread and agony for the rest of the film and that's before the horror aspect of the movie really starts to kick in. It is a slow burn which never usually bothers me but this movie almost lost me at a certain point until it finally drug me back in which is my one and only complaint. Other than that though, the cinematography and imagery, the score, the fucking top tier acting, and just the skillful execution by the director make this not just a good horror movie but a good film in general.. I would say don't go into this movie with the mindset that you're gonna see "the scariest movie ever"... go in to this movie with an open mind set and be prepared for a good story and character development, do that and the horror will hit you at the right moments

text: Ok. Watched the movie tonight.  Who said it was scary?  Not the trailer.   This is not the exorcist and it never claimed to be.   If your looking for all kinds of childish jump scares and to be grossed out forget it.  That‚Äôs for the kiddies.  If your looking for a thought provoking drama/ horror / about the demise of this family you will enjoy this film. It is a a story at a slow burn.  Not for those who can‚Äôt concentrate for more than 2 minutes without looking for their cellphone.  Ok. So it has a horror feel.  The anticipation of what the hell is going on and what is going to happen next just might keep your heart racing.  I loved this film. I would call it more of a psychological supernatural thriller/drama along the lines of the shining, which was not scary at all.  If your looking for Friday the 13th forget it.  This is nothing at all like those kind of idiotic horror movies.  This is for adults.  It can be shocking. You will feel some anxiety for sure. It is beautifully filmed with a fantastic performance by Toni Colette .  You will have to make your own decision on what the ending means to you. It‚Äôs thought provoking.  This poor family. Makes you think about what not to mess with in life. Be scared and be shocked. Be amazed and sink down in your seat and enjoy the ride but be prepared to think about this film for a while at night in your dreams.  Wicked!

text: So I watched this movie yesterday and I honestly didn't find it the least bit creepy/scary. Completely dull experience. Seriously was sooo slow until the last like 15 minutes which were more hilarious than anything else. I get the exposition was intentionally slow to build tension but it just didn't do it well in my opinion. Also, I love psychological and atmospheric horror and no, I don't have attention problems and followed the movie just fine. Was pretty straight forward. I can see where it would maybe be unsettling for people that spook easily or believe in hell and demonic stuff (I don't, just seems childish and silly).  I thought it was just okay at best and didn't do anything special to make it good. However, the comment section is filled with people raving about how scary it is and is the best horror film ever. Just wondering what people actually found scary about this movie? Not hating, just actually confused why this is being praised so highly.

text: I have an observation that may cause any sensible woman to cross the street opposite me once I reveal it.  Toni Collette is an attractive woman.  That's a benign enough a statement.  Yeaaaah, well, don't get too settled.    She manages to do, or perhaps just has the genetic fiber to pull off something that I have never seen done.   I have not seen this demonstrated in cinema, nor have I seen this demonstrated in reality.  This is a perceptual shake-up that threw me off my horse for lack of anticipation.   The aesthetic of terror and rage never deviate from a grotesque arrangement of muscles tissue and skin contour.  Distress draws vitality out of a face,  and fear dries up what remains of it.  Collette manages to improve her beauty index throughout the movie as her face contorts with sheer horror.  Is this a director's slight-of-hand?  I'm not confident that camera angles and lighting can bestow a cosmetic lift in the throws of panic and anguish.  Yet this happens over and over again in the movie.  You see her go from a tranquil appealing look, to becoming aghast with a greater seduction.     If this was done by design, bravo, there are magicians on set.  However this is something very new to me.   It is perplexing from a biological standpoint.  How would fear or rage ever be conducive to courtship?  I know this bit creepy but I must report what I see, especially if they are new to my psyche. text: Proof once again critics know squat about movies..  the lead actress is terrible in this,  way overacted, it was about as thrilling or scary as earnest goes to camp.   Maybe I'm jaded by the tens of thousands of horror movies I've seen, but  this is pretty far down the list as far as horror movies go.   It comes after 'it comes at night' from this newer studio,  which also tried to be a psychological thriller.  Both left me yawning knowing exactly what was coming the entire time. hereditary tried to be a psych. thriller for the first 2/3,  which it wasn't the worst effort ever but for all the hoopla surrounding it we can only conclude there is something very political going on in critic circles,  and for some reason they decided this studio must succeed.   The last third inexplicably turned into a 'jump scare fest' that failed miserably at that.  In the end we see where the hereditary part comes in as the demon is named,  only for the second time in the movie.   No backstory,  no explanation went we should give a crap what happens to these characters.    Just a lot of bad,  stiff acting with no depth of character and jump scares you can see coming from 10 miles.  Overall extremely disappointing after the critical acclaim,  2/10. We did learn long ago that horror movies with high praise are 99/100 pure garbage so i can't fault the critics,  they're doing what they've always done.

text: Hats off the worst horror movie I've watched and I managed to go through "Drag Me To Hell" without dying on the inside. What bothered me the most was the way mental disease was portrayed as being something to fear and loathe. Throw in some cringey, offenssive shit like decapitating an autistic girl and there you go. Listen, I know most horrors use mental disease as an underlying theme but I feel like this movie overdid it in a way that does even more damage to our society's already ignorant attitude toward mental illness. Also, the plot, my God, you get bored long before it starts to make sense, and until then it's just mental abuse. The really scary thing in this film is that people still don't get treatment for their psychological problems and instead of dealing with them, project on their kids. Satan ain't got nothing to do with that.

text: Disturbing , bizzare , depressing cynical garbage .  I cant even give it a " garbage done right " like Shining , Texas Chainsaw massacre , or Friday the 13th.  It tries to give a exorcist mixed with shining vibe , but the end ( as with most movies these days ) gives you no breathing space  Its just bam bam bam one weird violent thing after the other.   I have no idea whats in the mind of people that make this crap . There is no redeemable artistic value what so ever . Especially dealing with the sensitive topic of the death of a child. Even after the violent death of Charlie, i thought the movie might take an interesting turn and maybe the family has visions of things as a way to cope . No. Nope . Just devolves into supernatural horror and gore scenes with some very dopey weird satanism thrown in.  No wonder this country is so f'd up and we have nut jobs like Alex Jones saying Hollywood is satanic . Its obviously not , but when this garbage is put out there, it brings out the religious wackos¬†.¬† ¬†  I remember watching a movie as a kid called " don't look now " with Donald Sutherland¬† . After they find their daughter had drowned , it just filled me with sadness and blackness as a kid . Then the movie went into that supernatural crap . People die , children die , it shouldn't be a topic used in trash art horror movies . Its just shitty . It does nothing good for your mind .¬†  If you are young , its hard to get but life and happiness are things to treasure. Trust me . You get older , see a few loved ones die , and it flips your perspective . I have no need for this garbage.  But this is Merica , and we need that " freedumb " to do ridiculous shit i guess ...
